Case Study 2: How Can a Wellness Technology Company Play It Smart?
================
Quang Huy Vu
Sep 15, 2022

## Introduction:

This documentation is made to record all steps taken during the data
cleaning process for the first Google Data Analytics Certificate’s
capstone project.

The outline for this documentation would be:

1.  Set up the packages to manipulate raw data.

2.  Import and review data.

3.  Clean and format data for further analyses.

4.  Merge datasets.

## 1. Set up the packages to manipulate raw data

First, set up the packages for data wrangling and cleaning:

-   tidyverse: wrangle data.

-   lubridate: wrangle date attributes.

-   skimr: enable summary function for prescriptive analytics of each
    individual column.

-   janitor: check data compatibility and combine csv files.

``` r
library(tidyverse)
```

## 2. Import and review data

Firstly, we need to set working directory to the folder that has the
data.

``` r
setwd("D:/Learning/Google Data Analytics Certificate/Capstone Project/Project 2/data")
getwd()
```

    ## [1] "D:/Learning/Google Data Analytics Certificate/Capstone Project/Project 2/data"

And import the files to data frames.As steps/calories are included in
activity file, we will not import daily steps/daily calories csv files.

``` r
d_activity <- read.csv("daily_activity.csv")
d_sleep <- read.csv("daily_sleep.csv")
h_steps <- read.csv("hourly_steps.csv")
h_calories <- read.csv("hourly_calories.csv")
```

For daily data frames, they all had a ID column which represents user
identity and a date column. ID column has the same data type across data
frames, yet date has different formats. In order to merge the data for
further analyses, we will reformat this column to date.

``` r
d_activity <- d_activity %>% 
  rename(date = activitydate) %>% 
  mutate(date = as.Date(date,format = "%m/%d/%Y"))
         
d_sleep <- d_sleep %>% 
  rename(date = sleepday) %>% 
  mutate(date = as.Date(date,format = "%m/%d/%Y"))
```

Plus, for hourly data, activity hour columns are of string data type. We
would want to change it to date time data type for consistency.
